**Wu Marquis of Wei (魏武侯) was deliberating on important matters and, when he did so, none of his ministers could match his insight. After the court session ended, he had a look of joy on his face. Wu Risi (吳起) stepped forward and said:**

*"I once heard the following about King Zhao of Chu (楚莊王). When people nearby heard about his deliberations, none of his ministers could keep up with him. After court, he looked worried. Duke Shen (申公) asked one of his officials: 'Your Majesty looks worried after court. Why is that?' King Zhao replied:*

*‘It is because I deliberate on matters alone and none of my ministers can match me. That is why I am worried. There is a saying in the middle states (中蘭之言): "If a feudal lord relies on his own strength to raise an army, he becomes king; if he relies on his own strength to make friends, he becomes hegemon; if he relies on his own suspicions, he survives. But if he makes plans alone and finds no one as capable as himself, he is doomed to perish." Now, because I am not blessed with capable ministers, and none can match me, our state is close to ruin. That is why I am worried.’*

*King Zhao worries because he is alone in his wisdom, while Your Excellency (Wu Marquis) is happy because your ministers cannot match you. But actually, this is a sign of danger for your state. That is why he worries and you rejoice.’*

**Wu Marquis, deeply moved, bowed twice and said: ‘Heaven has sent you, sir, to correct my mistakes.’**

